ce:section.ce:para:
Herein, Cu-NCDs were synthesized by direct pyrolysis method using citric acid (CA) and thiourea (TU) and CuSO4·5H2O as precursors and Cu-NCDs as the fluorescent probe was developed for Fe3+ and TC detection (Fig. 1
                     ). The as-prepared Cu-NCDs showed strong blue fluorescence (λ
                     max = 450 nm). Further studies found that Fe3+ and TC could selectively and sensitively quench the fluorescence of Cu-NCDs. Owing to the above features, the Cu-NCDs were applied as a multifunctional sensor to detect two objects in environmental water, which achieved good recoveries of 96.1–100.6% and 98.2–100.9%, respectively. Moreover, H2O2 can transform Fe2+ into Fe3+ without affecting the intensity of the fluorescent probe so that Fe2+ can be measured indirectly in this system. Therefore, Cu-NCDs was expected to play a crucial role in sensing.
